Defendant Quincy Everett Salton in court with attorney Hazel Jean Washington.  Kimberly Dorice Schoepp appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy court clerk ccp.
Case set for sentencing hearing. Parties are preapred to proceed. State placed negotiations on the record. Statements made as to sentencing. Additional statements made by Saaire S.

As to COUNT 1 as AMENDED-
Court ordered defendant to serve 1 YEAR in the House of Correction, credit for 3 days time served. Defendant may have release for work if employed at the time of revocation and for school if enrolled at the time of revocation. Defendant may participate in vocational and/or educational programming at the House of Correction.

Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 30 MONTHS with the following conditions:
1) Court ordered 60 DAYS of condition time in the House of Correction. 15 DAYS to be served upfront. The remaining 45 DAYS are STAYED to be used at the discretion of the agent. 
2) AODA assessment and comply with recommended treatment;
3) Pay all costs, fees, surcharges and restitution during period of probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment;
4) Pay restitution in the amount of $500.00 to Peter B. and $250.00 to Kerri T. for a total of $750.00. Restitution to be paid FIRST before costs, fees and surcharges. Court will allow the defendant to enter into a payment plan with the agent;
5) Maintain employment of at least 30 hours per week. If not employed for 40 hours per week, defendant to be enrolled in school;
6) Participate in a cognitive thinking class;
7) Maintain absolute sobriety from all illegal drugs and alcohol;
8) No contact with the victims;
9) Provide DNA sample and pay DNA surcharge;

Expungment is authorized by the Court upon successful completion of probation. 

Defendant to report to the House of Correction to serve the 15 DAYS on 9/04/15 by 9:00 a.m. Defendant may have release for work and school if employed and if enrolled. 

If revoked, court costs, fees, surcharges and restitution be paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds and earnings.

